post_cb({"4842099": {"Id": "4842099", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It's by definition- a static object is one that's shared by all instances of the class.  Regular members don't have this property.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-01-30T09:14:41.493", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:14:41.493", "ParentId": "4842091", "Score": "3", "OwnerUserId": "501557"}, "4842122": {"Id": "4842122", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Because that's what <code>static</code> means in that context.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-01-30T09:19:38.137", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:19:38.137", "ParentId": "4842091", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "523612"}, "4842111": {"Id": "4842111", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Because class static members are stored separately in BSS section, so every instance of a class has the  same value.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-01-30T09:16:23.987", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:16:23.987", "ParentId": "4842091", "Score": "-1", "OwnerUserId": "595273"}, "4842101": {"Id": "4842101", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Because they would be <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instance_variable\" rel=\"nofollow\">instance members</a> then.</p>\n<p>The primary characteristic of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Class_variable\" rel=\"nofollow\">static members</a> is that they're shared by all the instances of the class.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-01-30T09:14:57.030", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:14:57.030", "ParentId": "4842091", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "464709"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_4842091_4842128_0": {"length": 15, "quality": 0.9375, "section_id": 5906}}, "n3337": {"so_4842091_4842128_0": {"length": 15, "quality": 0.9375, "section_id": 5678}}, "n4659": {"so_4842091_4842128_0": {"length": 15, "quality": 0.9375, "section_id": 7388}}}, "4842128": {"Id": "4842128", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Because the section $9.4.2/1 from the C++ Standard (2003) says,</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_4842091_4842128_0\"><strong>A static data member is not part of\n  the subobjects of a class. There is\n  only one copy of a static data member\n  shared by all the objects of the\n  class.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Since the Standard alone decides what C++ is, what not, so it's how C++ has been designed!</p>\n<p>Static members are more like global objects. The same copy belong to all objects!</p>\n<p>See this post for detail answer : <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4842056/do-static-members-of-a-class-occupy-memory-if-no-object-of-that-class-is-created/4842120#4842120\">Do static members of a class occupy memory if no object of that class is created?</a></p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2011-01-30T09:43:26.910", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:20:55.293", "ParentId": "4842091", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "415784", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T11:47:44.533"}, "4842097": {"Id": "4842097", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>A static member is not associated with a specific instance.</p>\n<p>If you want different values of the member for each instance you should use <em>instance</em> members (remove the static keyword).</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-01-30T09:14:32.620", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:14:32.620", "ParentId": "4842091", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "61974"}, "4842091": {"ViewCount": "200", "Body": "<p>Why don't we have different copies of static variables for the different objects?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "4842101", "Title": "Why are the static members of a class the same for all objects?", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:12:36.910", "Id": "4842091", "CommentCount": "2", "LastEditDate": "2011-02-05T22:59:41.257", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "252000", "LastActivityDate": "2011-02-05T22:59:41.257", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "379888", "Tags": "<c++><class><static>", "AnswerCount": "7"}, "4842108": {"Id": "4842108", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>That is the definition of <code>static</code> - one copy of the data exists.  It is separately stored, most likely along with all the other static data of the library or application.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-01-30T09:16:00.250", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-01-30T09:16:00.250", "ParentId": "4842091", "Score": "3", "OwnerUserId": "415892"}});